author: saleem-mirza
message:
Propagate user defined tags to instance and volumes in EKS nodes (#3639)

Attempted to tag spot-instance-request and elastic gpu
resources. Rolled back:

Currently, auto scaling group fails to launch managed node groups
if non-gpu instance types are tagged with elastic-gpu tag.
same is true with spot instances.
Disabling tagging gpu and spot for self-managed instances until
this bug is fixed.

Currently there is no effect of tagging on spot instance resources.
It appears like CloudFormation is not propagating tags to spot instance requests.

Will revisit if support improves.

author: rndstr
message:
Add command to manipulate IAM identity mappings

Adds the following commands to get/create/delete IAM role mappings to
Kubernetes username and groups.

    eksctl get iamidentitymapping [--role arn]
    eksctl create iamidentitymapping --role <arn> [--username=USER] --group=GROUP0 [--group=GROUP1]
    eksctl delete iamidentitymapping --role <arn> [--all]

`eksctl get iamidentitymapping`
Returns all mappings; if role filter is given it returns all matching
roles (can be more than one).

`eksctl create iamidentitymapping`
Allows creating duplicates. Will warn if duplicates exist.

`eksctl delete iamidentitymapping`
Deletes a single mapping FIFO unless `--all` is given in which case it
removes all matching. Will warn if more mappings matching this role are
found.

author: cPu1
message:
Enforce setting privateNetworking for fully-private clusters

privateNetworking for both self-managed and EKS-managed nodegroups must be set explicitly. It's an error to leave privateNetworking unset, as it's not possible to create public nodegroups in a fully-private cluster as there's no public subnet. Rather than enabling this field by default for a fully-private cluster, we require users to explicitly set it to make the behaviour explicit and avoid confusion.

author: marccarre
message:
Refactoring: move create cluster's CLI flags validation to Loader

... as this is where all validation happens.
`CreateClusterCmdParams#Validate()` is called in both:

- `validateWithConfigFile` and
- `validateWithoutConfigFile`

even though, currently, the validation logic is only relevant to the
"without config file" path, as this is how it logically should be.

The reason for grouping validation logic of `CreateClusterCmdParams`
in `CreateClusterCmdParams#Validate()` instead of in the validation
functions is that an object should generally be able to validate
itself, as opposed to "leaking" its field members to other code
for it to validate them.

author: cPu1
message:
Bring Windows integration test runtime down to less than half

This changelist parallelises the Windows integration test specs by modifying the integration test runner to accept arbitrary arguments to be passed to the `ginkgo` binary, allowing the integration test GitHub workflow to pass the `-p` and `--procs` arguments to parallelise running the test specs. This has brought the total runtime of Windows integration tests down to ~55 minutes from ~2 hours and 30 minutes.

The cluster version used in the tests has been updated to the latest EKS version 1.27, and as a result, one of the tests that uses the Docker runtime has been removed as it's no longer supported.

actually been deleted.

author: agbanagba
message:
Consistent description across flags using StringToString (#2160)

* Consistent desctiption across flags using StringToString

Changes to ensure there is a consistent description across flags using
StringToString. Change involved adding k1=v1,k2=v2 in the description
and also noting it is a list of KV pairs in all ocurrence of use.

Issue #1616

* String to string wrapper for description prefix

Flag Wrapper change to allow for a static description prefix across
future uses of the stringToString flag.

Fixes #1616

* StringToString description updates

StringToString flag common description comes after the flag specific
description. This change also removes examples in specific descriptions.

Fixes #1616

* StringToString tag description backticks

Backticks in flag specific description removed.

Fixes #1616

Co-authored-by: Michael Beaumont <mjboamail@gmail.com>

author: errordeveloper
message:
Add `eksctl utils describe-stacks --trail`

When different users create clusters in a single AWS account, it's not
very easy to tell who owns which cluster, and we shouldn't need to invent
our own means. CloudTrail works nicely for this (albeit with 90 day limit).
It's not very easy to "just use CloudTrail", as one needs to understand
query parameters. Filtering by cluster name is also very untrivial, as
one need CloudFormation stack ID (not just stack name).

The additional security groups can be used for allowing extra egress from/ingress to pods running on the nodes.

Resolves #397

author: hintofbasil
message:
Handle pod eviction errors correctly (#5116)

* Handle pod eviction errors correctly

Currently any eviction error causes the draining of a node to stop and a new
node to start draining.  Eviction errors are common, expected occurences
especially when PDBs are used in the cluster.
By having any error abort the draining of a node we slow down the entire node
draining process as many of the pods further in the list could happily be
drained.

This change separates recoverable and irrecoverable eviction errors and retries
only the recoverable.  Unrecoverable errors fail the entire command.

An important aspect of this is that the `evictPods` function becomes blocking
until a node is drained or the process times out.  This is required as the
current implementation begins draining another node on the first eviction
error.  We would rather keep trying and eventually time out than make a bad
situation worse by draining a new node.

* Update pkg/drain/nodegroup.go

Co-authored-by: Gergely Brautigam <182850+Skarlso@users.noreply.github.com>

author: rndstr
message:
Set kubeReserved defaults according to instance type

This change implements default values for `kube-reserved` the same way
as the [official AMIs] do which is dependent on the instance type.

Reserved memory and cpu are set according to a formula while the storage
is always set to 1GiB. See the source code for details.

Instance type information (such as available storage, memory, and cpu)
may not only change in the future but also new instances will be added.
There is a make target `generate-kube-reserved` which fetches all instance
types by querying the AWS API `ec2:DescribeInstanceTypes` in each
region. It then saves it to `pkg/nodebootstrap/reserved_data.go` ready
to be taken as input for computing appropriate default values.

[official AMIs]: https://github.com/awslabs/amazon-eks-ami/blob/master/files/bootstrap.sh

asdf

author: errordeveloper
message:
Use image as cache store

- there is no need to build the image in CI as a primary job
  - pulling the image is as quick as restoring cache
  - we can control what is being cached
  - we don't have to rely on how CircleCI cache works, so our
    jobs are more portable
- cleanup
  - remove outdated Skaffold config
  - cleanup Dockerfile, cache all of the modules, use GOPROXY
- upgrade CircleCI jobs' resource class
- start trial of GitHub Actions in parallel to CircleCI
  - start with two workflows
    - one is for running tests & building the binaries in pre-existing image
    - one for updating images
- split Docker-related targets from the main Makefile, avoiding
  having to have Go installed in CI job that builds images
- extract common variables into separate `Makefile.common`
- update modules that are used in the build
- fix file license header filename

message:
Check Fargate Profile existence while creating

When creating Fargate Profile from ClusterConfig file, it might need to
comment out existed on then create a new one. With this PR, an existed
Fargate Profile creation will be skipped before start.

```
% make binary
```

```
% ./eksctl version
0.122.0-dev+a5d7c20ba.2022-11-30T20:36:42Z
```

```
% ./eksctl create fargateprofile -f ./cluster-config/cluster-minimal.yaml
2022-11-30 20:50:12 [ℹ]  Fargate profile "demo-existed-profile" already exists on EKS cluster "eks-demo"
2022-11-30 20:50:12 [ℹ]  creating Fargate profile "demo-new-profile" on EKS cluster "eks-demo"

...

author: richardcase
message:
Generation of static AMI list

The list of AMIs to use for the static resolver is now generated
via go:generate. The list is queried from AWS and output to a code
file.

A separate makefile target called 'generate-ami' has been added that
runs go generate. The reason for a separate target is the fact that
AWS credentials are required for the code generation and this would
break the current workflow for the 'generate' target.

Another makefile target called 'ami-check' has been added. The
intended purpose of this by an automated scheduled process that
will run to check if new images are available.

Issue #49

message:
Have kubelet use systemd cgroup driver on al2 and ubuntu

Kubernetes documentation indicates that for stability reasons
one should run kubernetes with the systemd cgroup driver if the
init system itself is systemd.

https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/production-environment/container-runtimes/#cgroup-drivers

The same change is also be made in awslabs/amazon-eks-ami:

https://github.com/awslabs/amazon-eks-ami/pull/521

author: cPu1
message:
Fix updating kube-proxy to a newer version

The version returned by `DescribeAddonVersions` cannot be used as-is for kube-proxy as it does not always map to the container image version. But for now, it does map to the minimal image tag.

This changelist adds a `minimal` string to the version obtained from `DescribeAddonVersions` to map it to a valid container image.

author: D3nn
message:
Readded the ability to delete a cluster before it's finished creating

A previous PR (#1010) made it a prerequisite that an EKS cluster must
be in an ACTIVE state before `eksctl delete cluster` would be able to
delete the cluster.  This was done to find all the ELBs that were
created due to services in the cluster.  However, if a cluster isn't
created, there can be no ELBs created for the cluster, so this
PR removes that restriction and adds some integration tests for
this use case.

author: richardcase
message:
Reworked region logic

Changed the the region logic so that if we create a AWS session
and there is no region from either the flags, aws shared config,
and aws environment variables then we re-create the session again
but specifying a default region. This is less than ideal but the
shared config isn't loaded until we create new session and the code
to read the shared config (ini files) is private.

A new issue will be opened to change this in the future to be cleaner
but we need a change to the AWS SDK first.

Signed-off-by: Richard Case <richard.case@outlook.com>

Added the ability to override the kube config cluster server.

This change allows users with a private cluster to be able to use SSH
tunnelling to access the cluster from their local machine via a
port other than 443.

The KUBECONFIG_CLUSTER_ENDPOINT environment variable can now be
set to override the cluster endpoint in the kube config object
that's generated via kubeconfig.go.

This change references #1552 and #1618

author: errordeveloper
message:
Filter out serviceaccounts that exist in Kubernetes

Due to security considerations default behaviour of
`eksctl create iamserviceaccount` should exclude
updates to the metadata on serviceaccounts that already
exit in Kubernetes. That is in order to prevent a
case where user inadvertedly grats new priveleges to
some pods that are already running.
It's important to note that there may exist pods that
are referencing a serviceaccount which do not exists,
so it's still possible to grant access inadvertedly,
however there is not much that we can do about that
and users should consider an apropriate policy and
RBAC rules to prevent security risks.

author: dcherman
message:
Make scaling operations for nodegroups idempotent

CloudFormation throws an error when attempting to submit a changeset to a
stack that contains no actual changes.  This can occur when you attempt to
scale a NodeGroup to the same size that it already is.  To work-around
that, we can detect if you're attempting to scale the NodeGroup to the
existing DesiredCapacity and turn that action into a no-op in order to
make this API call idempotent.

Fixes #430

author: richardcase
message:
Persist valuf of --profile to Kubeconf

If you specify a profile using the `--profile` flag when creating
a cluster then the value of the profile flag will be saved to the
kubectl configuration for heptio-authenticator-aws. If you specify
a profile using `AWS_PROFILE` then it won't be persisted to the config.

Issue #70

NAME		SELECTOR_NAMESPACE	SELECTOR_LABELS	POD_EXECUTION_ROLE_ARN										SUBNETS
fp-bc364107	default			<none>		arn:aws:iam::083751696308:role/eksctl-mc-1664-test-cluste-FargatePodExecutionRole-VHHN3M9X5IBX	subnet-01f27f9c008fe197d,subnet-0b42d9d42f7eb92bf,subnet-06de09d669eb78152
fp-dev		dev			<none>		arn:aws:iam::083751696308:role/eksctl-mc-1664-test-cluste-FargatePodExecutionRole-VHHN3M9X5IBX	subnet-01f27f9c008fe197d,subnet-0b42d9d42f7eb92bf,subnet-06de09d669eb78152

$ ./eksctl delete fargateprofile
Error: --cluster must be set

author: mumoshu
message:
Group cluster create flags for readability

`eksctl create cluster -h` now looks like:

```
Create a cluster

Usage:
  eksctl create cluster [flags]

Node Flags:
      --asg-access                enable iam policy dependency for cluster-autoscaler
      --full-ecr-access           enable full access to ECR
      --max-pods-per-node int     maximum number of pods per node (set automatically if unspecified)
      --node-ami string           Advanced use cases only. If 'static' is supplied (default) then eksctl will use static AMIs; if 'auto' is supplied then eksctl will automatically set the AMI based on region/instance type; if any other value is supplied it will override the AMI to use for the nodes. Use with extreme care. (default "static")
      --node-ami-family string    Advanced use cases only. If 'AmazonLinux2' is supplied (default), then eksctl will use the offical AWS EKS AMIs (Amazon Linux 2); if 'Ubuntu1804' is supplied, then eksctl will use the offical Canonical EKS AMIs (Ubuntu 18.04). (default "AmazonLinux2")
  -P, --node-private-networking   whether to make initial nodegroup networking private
  -t, --node-type string          node instance type (default "m5.large")
      --node-volume-size int      Node volume size (in GB)
  -N, --nodes int                 total number of nodes (desired capacity of ASG) (default 2)
  -M, --nodes-max int             maximum nodes in ASG (leave unset for a static nodegroup)
  -m, --nodes-min int             minimum nodes in ASG (leave unset for a static nodegroup)
      --ssh-access                control SSH access for nodes
      --ssh-public-key string     SSH public key to use for nodes (import from local path, or use existing EC2 key pair) (default "~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub")
      --storage-class             if true (default) then a default StorageClass of type gp2 provisioned by EBS will be created (default true)

Networking Flags:
      --vpc-cidr ipNet                 global CIDR to use for VPC (default 192.168.0.0/16)
      --vpc-from-kops-cluster string   re-use VPC from a given kops cluster
      --vpc-private-subnets strings    re-use private subnets of an existing VPC
      --vpc-public-subnets strings     re-use public subnets of an existing VPC
      --zones strings                  (auto-select if unspecified)

Stack Flags:
  -r, --region string         AWS region
      --tags stringToString   A list of KV pairs used to tag the AWS resources (e.g. "Owner=John Doe,Team=Some Team") (default [])

Other Flags:
      --auto-kubeconfig          save kubeconfig file by cluster name, e.g. "/Users/kuoka-yusuke/.kube/eksctl/clusters/adorable-monster-1543548069"
      --kubeconfig string        path to write kubeconfig (incompatible with --auto-kubeconfig) (default "/Users/kuoka-yusuke/.kube/config")
  -n, --name string              EKS cluster name (generated if unspecified, e.g. "adorable-monster-1543548069")
  -p, --profile string           AWS credentials profile to use (overrides the AWS_PROFILE environment variable)
      --set-kubeconfig-context   if true then current-context will be set in kubeconfig; if a context is already set then it will be overwritten (default true)
      --timeout duration         max wait time in any polling operations (default 20m0s)
      --write-kubeconfig         toggle writing of kubeconfig (default true)

Global Flags:
  -C, --color         toggle colorized logs (default true)
  -v, --verbose int   set log level, use 0 to silence, 4 for debugging and 5 for debugging with AWS debug logging (default 3)
```

Ref #298

author: richardcase
message:
AMI resolution and overriding (allowing GPU support) (#192)

The `--node-ami` flag has been added and can be used to supply an ami id to use. There are
2 special values that can be passed as well:

- 'static' which is the default and it will make sure the static
resolvers are used (which uses embedded image ids)
- 'auto' which instructs eksctl to use the 'auto' resolver (which queries AWS).

If neither of these special values are supplied to the flag then we take it as a excplicit AMI image id that should be used for the EKS nodes.

The 'static' and 'auto' resolvers can resolve instance types with GPU support (p2/p3) and use an AMI image that is optimized with GPU support. If using the GPU instances then the [NVIDIA device plugin](https://github.com/NVIDIA/k8s-device-plugin) will still need to be installed manually. Instructions are output. This will be an 'addon' in the future.

The ami's used for non-gpu instances have been updated to use the v23 version of the images. Also added the image for eu-west-1.

The static resolvers use maps to aid future go generate code which will aid #49.

After changing the AMIs to v23 a change has been made to use aws-iam-authenticator instead of heptio-authenticator-aws.

Also, AMI resolution is done earlier before the stack is started to be built...fail fast. Also added code to check the resolved image exists.

Issue #183 
Issue #197 
Issue #194
Issue #169

author: mgalgs
message:
docs: autoscaling: Add note about ASG tags for scaling up from 0

When the cluster-autoscaler adds a new node to a group, it grabs an
existing node in the group and builds a "template" to launch a new node
identical to the one it grabbed from the group.

However, when scaling up from 0 there aren't any live nodes to reference to
build this template.  Instead, the cluster-autoscaler relies on tags in the
ASG to build the new node template.  This can cause unexpected behavior if
the pods triggering the scale-out are using node selectors or taints; CA
doesn't have sufficient information to decide if a new node launched in the
group will satisfy the request.

The long and short of it is that for CA to do its job properly we must tag
our ASGs corresponding to our labels and taints.  Add a note in the docs
about this since scaling up from 0 is a fairly common use case.

References:

  - https://github.com/kubernetes/autoscaler/issues/2418
  - https://github.com/weaveworks/eksctl/issues/1066

author: marccarre
message:
eksctl install flux now handles re-installation (by deleting only Flux-related resources, and re-creating them) (#1225)

* Extract duplicate logic to RawResource#exists

Keeping things DRY should help with readability, reusability,
quality, etc.

* Add RawResource#Delete

* Add RawClient#Delete

* Add RawResource#Exists

* Add RawClient#Exists

* Installing Flux now deletes pre-existing resources

... prior to creating them again.

Indeed, the user's first installation might have partially failed,
or the user may want to reinstall Flux for whatever reason, but the
current implementation fails on a 2nd installation.

This is because `CreateOrUpdate` is not idempotent and fails on the
more complex objects, with important values defaulted server-side
like `Service` objects' IP addresses.

An alternative approach would be to use `kubectl apply` but this
would introduce a dependency on `kubectl`.

Note that we do NOT delete Flux's private SSH key, so that the user
does not have to set up Flux's permissions again in his repository.

* (Re-)create Flux Helm secrets prior to (re-)creating Flux

Otherwise, upon a re-installation, Flux will start with old certs,
and `eksctl` then times out:

```console
[ℹ]  Waiting for Helm Operator to start
[...]
ERROR: logging before flag.Parse: E0829 17:28:35.778721   88133 portforward.go:331] an error occurred forwarding 49582 -> 3030: error forwarding port 3030 to pod 8e705fc70fe04bb25ec354655785ef71fa025e345e091c5349a56fc8309ed4a2, uid : exit status 1: 2019/08/29 08:28:35 socat[18057] E connect(5, AF=2 127.0.0.1:3030, 16): Connection refused
[!]  Helm Operator is not ready yet (Get http://127.0.0.1:49582/healthz: EOF), retrying ...
[...]
[✖]  timed out waiting for Helm Operator to be operative
```

```console
$ kubectl -n flux logs --follow flux-helm-operator-6bc7c85bb5-qsvqp
caller=helm.go:84 component=helm warning="unable to connect to Tiller"
err="error getting tiller version: context deadline exceeded"
host=tiller-deploy.flux:44134 options="{
  Host: Port: Namespace:flux TLSVerify:true TLSEnable:true
  TLSKey:/etc/fluxd/helm/tls.key TLSCert:/etc/fluxd/helm/tls.crt
  TLSCACert:/etc/fluxd/helm-ca/ca.crt TLSHostname:
}"
```

Note that the namespace is passed as it may be required before
creating the secrets, otherwise, `eksctl` would fail with:
```
[✖]  namespaces "flux" not found
```

* Fix state-related bug in fake Kubernetes client

* Add tests for RawResource#{Exists,Delete}

* Rename RawResource#Delete -> DeleteSync

* Create Flux namespace w/o side-effect for secrets

author: richardcase
message:
Added AWS Profile Support

Changes to ensure that AWS profiles are supported. This involved making
sure that the AWS config file is loaded (SharedConfigEnabled) and
also making sure we have a TokenProvider set.

Added an explicit --profile flag that can be used to explicity specify
which AWS profile you would like to use. This will override any profile
that you have specified via AWS_PROFILE.

If endpoints are being overriden then the credentials from the initial
session creation are shared with any subsequent session creation to
ensure that the tokens are shared (otherwise you may get multiple MFA
prompts).

Issue #57

author: marccarre
message:
Fargate: update aws-sdk-go

```console
$ cd ${GOPATH}/src/github.com/weaveworks-aws/aws-sdk-go
$ git remote -v
origin	git@github.com:weaveworks-aws/aws-sdk-go.git (fetch)
origin	git@github.com:weaveworks-aws/aws-sdk-go.git (push)
upstream	git@github.com:aws/aws-sdk-go (fetch)
upstream	git@github.com:aws/aws-sdk-go (push)
$ git fetch upstream master
$ git merge --ff-only upstream/master
$ git co -b staging-sdk303621037
$ find . -name "*.go" -type f -delete
$ cp -r /path/to/tmp/release-automation/staging-sdk303621037/sdk/src/github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go/* .
$ git add *
$ git commit -S -m "Update from staging-sdk303621037 copy shared by AWS"
$ make
$ git push origin staging-sdk303621037
$ git tag -a staging-sdk303621037 -m "staging-sdk303621037"
$ git push origin :refs/tags/staging-sdk303621037
$ go get -u github.com/weaveworks-aws/aws-sdk-go@staging-sdk303621037
$ export GOPRIVATE=github.com/weaveworks-aws
$ go get -u github.com/weaveworks-aws/aws-sdk-go@staging-sdk303621037
go: finding github.com/weaveworks-aws/aws-sdk-go staging-sdk303621037
go: downloading github.com/weaveworks-aws/aws-sdk-go v1.25.14-0.20191128064856-d39dadebcc3f
go: extracting github.com/weaveworks-aws/aws-sdk-go v1.25.14-0.20191128064856-d39dadebcc3f
go get: github.com/weaveworks-aws/aws-sdk-go@v1.25.14-0.20191128064856-d39dadebcc3f: parsing go.mod:
	module declares its path as: github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go
	        but was required as: github.com/weaveworks-aws/aws-sdk-go
```

```console
$ cd ${GOPATH}/src/github.com/weaveworks/eksctl
$ export GOPRIVATE=github.com/weaveworks-aws
$ GO111MODULE=on go mod verify
all modules verified
$ GO111MODULE=on go mod tidy
```

author: richardcase
message:
Get cluster fixes (#153)

Changed the 'list clusters' functionality:

- If there are no clusters and you are using the table printer then No clusters found will be output. If you are using the JSON or YAML printers then an empty array is returned. Fixes #146.
- If specifying a clustername and the cluster doesn't have a status of ClusterStatusActive then it will still print its details. Before this it was ignored. Fixes #145.
- Added additional tests to support the above and started to refactor tests so common 'fake' creation is separated out.

author: paulbes
message:
Permissions Boundary

A permissions boundary is an advanced IAM feature in which you set the
maximum permissions that an identity-based policy can grant to an IAM
entity; where those entities are either users or roles. When you set
a permissions boundary for an entity, the entity can perform only the
actions that are allowed by both its identity-based policies and its
permissions boundaries.

This is relevant for eksctl, because eksctl is capable of managing,
i.e., creating, updating and deleting, the identity-based resources
required to operate a kubernetes cluster on AWS. While it is possible
to create these identity entities outside of eksctl and provide them
as configuration options, this adds an additional burden on the end-user,
which it is preferable to avoid.

Support for providing a permissions boundary to the identity-based entities
has been added to eksctl by extending the configuration file primarily.
This decision was made based on the fact that serviceRoleARN for a cluster
is provided in a similar way today. The assumption here is that providing
a permissions boundary is not the common case, and should therefore not
pollute the CLI more than necessary.

Issue #1221

author: errordeveloper
message:
Disable zone filter, add flag to set zones manually

This the only sane way to fix UnsupportedAvailabilityZoneException,
espcially because it turns out that this is somehow different in every
AWS account (at least that what seems to be the case from the docs.

> You may receive an error that one of the Availability Zones in your
> request does not have sufficient capacity to create an Amazon EKS
> cluster. If this happens, the error output contains the Availability
> Zones that can support a new cluster. Retry creating your cluster
> with at least two subnets that are located in the supported
> Availability Zones for your account.

In the future we may try parsing the error message and retrying
automatically, but it doesn't seem feasible right now as we would
need to improve some of the internals and provide stack update
functionality.

author: elementalvoid
message:
Added `kubeReserved` calculation support for mixed instance NodeGroups (#2378)

* Added kubeReserved calculation support for mixed instance NodeGroups

Support for calculating CPU, RAM, and Storage reservations via
`kubeReserved` was added to eksctl in v0.16. However, it only supported
NodeGroups with a single instance type. ASGs can have multiple
instance types and were not included in the calculation.

This change enables calculation of kubeReserved for mixed instances too.
Since multiple instance types are supported it calculates the reservation
based on the smallest instance type in the distribution.

Additional kubeReserved tests covering unknown innstance types. The new tests
ensure that unknown instance types are properly ignored during calculation
of kubeReserved.

* Update userdocs/src/usage/customizing-the-kubelet.md

Co-authored-by: Martina Iglesias <martina-if@users.noreply.github.com>

author: cPu1
message:
Ignore IAM OIDC errors if no OIDC provider is associated with cluster

This changelist tags the cluster with the value of iam.withOIDC to allow eksctl to determine during cluster deletion if an OIDC provider was associated with the cluster or not.
Upon encountering an IAM permissions error, it throws an error if the cluster has an OIDC provider associated with it, which is determined either by the tag, or by the presence of IAM service accounts for clusters that lack the tag.

author: jalaziz
message:
Add default security group rules to custom SGs

Automatically add ingress rules to allow unmanaged nodes to communicate
with the cluster control plane and managed nodes when a custom shared
node security group is provided. Previously, these rules were only
created when the shared node security group was managed by eksctl.

To retain the previous behavior, we now provide a new
ManageSharedNodeSecurityGroupRules option which can be disabled.

Issue #3015

author: marccarre
message:
Fargate: get profile --name/arg behaves properly

**Before**

```console
$ ./eksctl get fargateprofile --name fp-a9318e0a
[...]
[✖]  --cluster must be set

$ ./eksctl get fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate
NAME		SELECTOR_NAMESPACE	SELECTOR_LABELS	POD_EXECUTION_ROLE_ARN										SUBNETS
fp-a9318e0a	dev			<none>		arn:aws:iam::083751696308:role/eksctl-marc-test-fargate-c-FargatePodExecutionRole-93J8HBVZF8KY	subnet-02ab167f0c03e2f3b,subnet-043e7465173101391,subnet-045e89931717f255c
fp-default	default			<none>		arn:aws:iam::083751696308:role/eksctl-marc-test-fargate-c-FargatePodExecutionRole-93J8HBVZF8KY	subnet-02ab167f0c03e2f3b,subnet-043e7465173101391,subnet-045e89931717f255c
fp-default	kube-system		<none>		arn:aws:iam::083751696308:role/eksctl-marc-test-fargate-c-FargatePodExecutionRole-93J8HBVZF8KY	subnet-02ab167f0c03e2f3b,subnet-043e7465173101391,subnet-045e89931717f255c

$ ./eksctl get fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate fp-a9318e0a
[...]
[✖]  --cluster=marc-test-fargate and argument fp-a9318e0a cannot be used at the same time

$ ./eksctl get fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate --name fp-a9318e0a
NAME		SELECTOR_NAMESPACE	SELECTOR_LABELS	POD_EXECUTION_ROLE_ARN										SUBNETS
fp-a9318e0a	dev			<none>		arn:aws:iam::083751696308:role/eksctl-marc-test-fargate-c-FargatePodExecutionRole-93J8HBVZF8KY	subnet-02ab167f0c03e2f3b,subnet-043e7465173101391,subnet-045e89931717f255c

$ ./eksctl get fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate --name fp-a9318e0a fp-default
[...]
[✖]  --cluster=marc-test-fargate and argument fp-default cannot be used at the same time
```

**After**

```console
$ ./eksctl get fargateprofile --name fp-a9318e0a
[...]
[✖]  --cluster must be set

$ ./eksctl get fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate
NAME		SELECTOR_NAMESPACE	SELECTOR_LABELS	POD_EXECUTION_ROLE_ARN										SUBNETS

author: dlespiau
message:
build: Make `make help` more pleasant

Currently make help displays its implementation details:

```
$ make
awk 'BEGIN {FS = ":.*##"; printf "\nUsage:\n  make \033[36m<target>\033[0m\n"} /^[a-zA-Z_-]+:.*?##/ { printf "  \033[36m%-15s\033[0m %s\n", $1, $2 } /^##@/ { printf "\n\033[1m%s\033[0m\n", substr($0, 5) } '  Makefile

Usage:
  make <target>
...
```

We don't need to see that awk command and the new line before Usage.

author: Tolsto
message:
Add option to specify IAM role name

Currently, CloudFormation generates a role name that contains
a random suffix. However, in some use-cases a predetermined
role name is useful. For instance, when following a git-ops
workflow it might be necessary to include the serviceaccount
annotations for the IAM role ARNs in the manifest repo. With
random role names that can only be done after the role has
been created by eksctl. In addition, if the cluster should ever
get re-created all role ARNs would change which would then
require all manifests that reference those ARNs to be edited.

Closes #2261

author: marccarre
message:
Fargate: create profile --name/arg behaves properly

**Before**

```console
$ ./eksctl create fargateprofile --namespace dev
[...]
[✖]  --cluster must be set

$ ./eksctl create fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate --namespace dev
[ℹ]  created Fargate profile "fp-136b0f42" on EKS cluster "marc-test-fargate

$ ./eksctl create fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate --namespace dev fp-dev
[...]
[✖]  --cluster=marc-test-fargate and argument fp-dev cannot be used at the same time

$ ./eksctl create fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate --namespace dev --name fp-dev
[ℹ]  created Fargate profile "fp-dev" on EKS cluster "marc-test-fargate"

$ ./eksctl create fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate --namespace dev --name fp-dev fp-test
[...]
[✖]  --cluster=marc-test-fargate and argument fp-test cannot be used at the same time
```

**After**

```console
$ ./eksctl create fargateprofile --namespace dev
[...]
[✖]  --cluster must be set

$ ./eksctl create fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate --namespace dev
[ℹ]  created Fargate profile "fp-35a0402f" on EKS cluster "marc-test-fargate

$ ./eksctl create fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate --namespace dev fp-dev
[ℹ]  created Fargate profile "fp-dev" on EKS cluster "marc-test-fargate"

$ ./eksctl create fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate --namespace dev --name fp-dev
[ℹ]  created Fargate profile "fp-dev" on EKS cluster "marc-test-fargate"

$ ./eksctl create fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate --namespace dev --name fp-dev fp-test
[...]
[✖]  --name=fp-dev and argument fp-test cannot be used at the same time
```

author: arnaldo2792
message:
Differentiate among accelerated hardware providers

`IsGPUInstanceType` groups all together NVIDIA and inferentia instances
which makes it difficult to reuse for OS'es that don't vend one image
with support for multiple accelerated hardware.

With this change, the instances with support for NVIDIA GPUs are
separated in its own function (like inferentia instances), which is
called by `IsGPUInstanceType`.

Signed-off-by: Arnaldo Garcia Rincon <agarrcia@amazon.com>

Simplify stack output getter

of outputs was assumed to increase over time and evolve a lot.
However, as ClusterConfig destination struct has evolved, this was no

NodeGroup struct has evolved also and needed intermediary struct too.
The number of outputs turned out to stabilise over time and this kind
complexity is pretty useless now.

author: mumoshu
message:
feat: Instance ID Node Label

Resolves #500

Manually verified to work by creating a new cluster and looking into node labels:

```console
$ k get no --show-labels
NAME                                             STATUS    ROLES     AGE       VERSION   LABELS
ip-10-1-11-239.ap-northeast-1.compute.internal   Ready     <none>    7m        v1.11.5   alpha.eksctl.io/cluster-name=staging-sre-1,alpha.eksctl.io/instance-id=i-08553f41b298f910e,alpha.eksctl.io/nodegroup-name=nodegroup1,beta.kubernetes.io/arch=amd64,beta.kubernetes.io/instance-type=t3.large,beta.kubernetes.io/os=linux,failure-domain.beta.kubernetes.io/region=ap-northeast-1,failure-domain.beta.kubernetes.io/zone=ap-northeast-1a,kubernetes.io/hostname=ip-10-1-11-239.ap-northeast-1.compute.internal
```

Each node's instance ID is set for the key `alpha.eksctl.io/instance-id`. Because the key is preficed with `alpha`, I'm fine with this being changed in a backward-incompatible way.

This should remain an useful feature until the instance-id-as-node-name feature is implemented in the upstream. See #509 to track the progress towards it.

author: mumoshu
message:
feat: Node-local DNS cache support

Add a new field named `clusterDNS` that accepts the IP address to the DNS server used for all the internal/external DNS lookups a.k.a the `--cluster-dns` flag of `kubelet`.

```yaml
nodeGroups:
- name: nodegroup1
  clusterDNS: 169.254.20.10
  # snip
```

This, in combination with `k8s-dns-node-cache` deployed as a daemonset on your cluster, allows all the DNS lookups from your pods to firstly routed to the node-local DNS server, which adds more reliability.

The configuration key `clusterDNS` is intentionally made per-nodegroup, not per-cluster, so that you can selectively use the node-local DNS. It, in combination with the proper use of node labels/taints, allows you to test the node-local DNS in only a subet of your workload.
It would also be nice to add `clusterDNS` as a cluster-level config key later. But I believe it isn't a must-have in this change.

See the [cluster/addons/dns/nodelocaldns](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/tree/master/cluster/addons/dns/nodelocaldns) in the upstream repository for more details.

A concrete steps to enable node-local DNS would look like the below:

- Decide the which IP addr to be used for binding the node-local DNS. Typically this is `169.254.20.10`
- Add `clusterDNS: 169.254.20.10` to your nodegroup in the cluster config
- Deploy [nodelocaldns.yaml](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/master/cluster/addons/dns/nodelocaldns/nodelocaldns.yaml), replacing:
  `__PILLAR__LOCAL__DNS__` with `169.254.169.254`, `__PILLAR__DNS__DOMAIN__` with `cluster.local`, `__PILLAR__DNS__SERVER__` with [`10.100.0.10` or `172.20.0.10`](https://github.com/weaveworks/eksctl/blob/master/pkg/nodebootstrap/userdata.go#L87-L94) according to your VPC CIDR

Resolves #542

author: marccarre
message:
Eagerly validates eksctl gitops apply's --output-path (#1336)

* Extract validation logic to options#validate method

It makes sense for the `options` DTO to be able to validate itself.
It also separate the "what" from the "how" of the validation logic, hence making `doApplyGitops` more readable.

* Add utility to check if dir is empty (+tests)

* Clean up: remove space, sort imports

* gitops apply: validate --output-path ASAP

* Fix typo/grammar in pkg/ctl/gitops/apply.go

Thanks @martina-if!

Co-Authored-By: Martina Iglesias <martina-if@users.noreply.github.com>

of the embedded structs.

Closes #2020

author: icereed
message:
Handle aws-node 1.7 initContainer properly

Since version 1.7 of AWS VPC CNI plugin for Kubernetes
the DaemonSet consists additionally of one initContainer.

This initContainer needs the same treatment as the main container regarding
usage of the regional image.

Otherwise the consequence would be a failing pod in China regions
or slow image pulls in other regions than us-west-2.

Commands act on a principal resource which may be a cluster or not. Most
commands act in the context of a cluster and as such need to receive its
name.

In case of the prinicpal resource being a cluster (such as `eksctl get cluster`)
the flag name is `--name`. For all other commands, the cluster name is
being passed in as `--cluster`.

author: marccarre
message:
Make ITs more robust to long cluster names

CloudFormation seems to truncate long cluster names, hence
integration tests were failing on regex matching:

```
[3]         /src/integration/tests/crud/creategetdelete_test.go:345
[3]
[3]         Expected
[3]             <string>: arn:aws:iam::123:role/eksctl-it-crud-wonderful-sculpture-158493288-Role1-1GY15K7ZJLBWV
[3]         to match regular expression
[3]             <string>: ^arn:aws:iam::.*:role/eksctl-it-crud-wonderful-sculpture-1584932889.*$
[3]
[3]         /src/integration/tests/crud/creategetdelete_test.go:402
```

```
[3]         /src/integration/tests/crud/creategetdelete_test.go:519
[3]
[3]         Expected
[3]             <string>: arn:aws:sts::456:assumed-role/eksctl-it-crud-wonderful-sculpture-158493288-Role1-1D0SFXFEJQL5/integration-test
[3]         to match regular expression
[3]             <string>: ^arn:aws:sts::.*:assumed-role/eksctl-it-crud-wonderful-sculpture-1584932889-.*/integration-test$
[3]
[3]         /src/integration/tests/crud/creategetdelete_test.go:570
```

This change addresses that by also truncating long cluster names
for expected values.

author: guessi
message:
Fix incorrect version info for command "eksctl info"

Issue description:

Command `eksctl info` reported the wrong version info of `kubectl`

    $ eksctl info
    eksctl version: 0.97.0
    kubectl version: v4.5.4 # <---- it's actually the version of Kustomize.
    OS: darwin

    $ kubectl version --client --short
    Flag --short has been deprecated, and will be removed in the future. The --short output will become the default. # <---- stderr.
    Client Version: v1.24.0 # <---- what we really need
    Kustomize Version: v4.5.4

To resolve this issue, change to use `--output json` and retrieve version information from "gitVersion".

    $ kubectl version --client --output json
    {
      "clientVersion": {
        "major": "1",
        "minor": "24",
        "gitVersion": "v1.24.0", # <---- get this version information as output.
        "gitCommit": "4ce5a8954017644c5420bae81d72b09b735c21f0",
        "gitTreeState": "clean",
        "buildDate": "2022-05-03T13:36:49Z",
        "goVersion": "go1.18.1",
        "compiler": "gc",
        "platform": "darwin/amd64"
      },
      "kustomizeVersion": "v4.5.4"
    }

Test result:

    $ go test
    Running Suite: <path>/eksctl/pkg/info/info_suite_test.go - <path>/eksctl/pkg/info
    =================================================================================
    Random Seed: 1652781848

    Will run 2 of 2 specs
    ••

    Ran 2 of 2 Specs in 0.103 seconds
    SUCCESS! -- 2 Passed | 0 Failed | 0 Pending | 0 Skipped
    PASS
    ok  	github.com/weaveworks/eksctl/pkg/info	0.875s

author: mumoshu
message:
Unattended Flux installation for GitHub repos (automatic addition of deploy key) (#2274)

Unattended Flux installation (automatic addition of deploy key)

You don't need to manually add GitHub deploy keys anymore.

This feature enables you to install Flux via eksctl in an unattended way, by automatically creating GitHub deply key on cluster creation and on `eksctl enable repo`, and by automatically deleting the deploy key on cluster deletion.

All you need to use this feature is providing `GITHUB_TOKEN` that has access to your repository's deploy keys, and a standard cluster.yaml that contains a `git` configuration for installing Flux.

Usage:

```
$ eksctl create cluster -f cluster.yaml

eksctl automatically creates a deploy key named  `eksctl-REGION-NAME` from the public ssh key generated by Flux
```

```
$ eksctl delete cluster -f cluster.yaml

eksctl automatically deletes the deploy key named `eksctl-REGION-NAME` by calling GitHub API
```

```
$ eksctl enable repo -f cluster.yaml

eksctl automatically creates a deploy key named  `eksctl-REGION-NAME` from the public ssh key generated by Flux
```

Please also note that this feature has an extra ability to make the deploy key "read-only". With the read-only deploy key, If you prefer that, you can effectively block Flux from ever pushing commits to the repository.

This can be enabled by setting `git.readOnly` to `true` or passing `--readonly` to `eksctl enable repo`.

Resolves #2273

author: marccarre
message:
Fargate: delete profile --name/arg behaves properly

**Before**

```console
$ ./eksctl delete fargateprofile --name fp-a9318e0a
[...]
[✖]  --cluster must be set

$ ./eksctl delete fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate
[...]
[✖]  invalid Fargate profile: empty name

$ ./eksctl delete fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate --name fp-a9318e0a
[ℹ]  deleted Fargate profile "fp-a9318e0a" on EKS cluster "marc-test-fargate"

$ ./eksctl delete fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate fp-3e1852b1
[...]
[✖]  --cluster=marc-test-fargate and argument fp-3e1852b1 cannot be used at the same time

$ ./eksctl delete fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate --name fp-136b0f42 fp-3e1852b1
[...]
[✖]  --cluster=marc-test-fargate and argument fp-3e1852b1 cannot be used at the same time

$ ./eksctl delete fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate --name ""
[...]
[✖]  invalid Fargate profile: empty name
```

**After**

```console
$ ./eksctl delete fargateprofile --name fp-a9318e0a
[...]
[✖]  --cluster must be set

$ ./eksctl delete fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate
[...]
[✖]  invalid Fargate profile: empty name

$ ./eksctl delete fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate --name fp-fp-
[ℹ]  deleted Fargate profile "fp-fp-" on EKS cluster "marc-test-fargate"

$ ./eksctl delete fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate fp-35a0402f
[ℹ]  deleted Fargate profile "fp-35a0402f" on EKS cluster "marc-test-fargate"

$ ./eksctl delete fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate --name fp-3e1852b1 fp-dev
[...]
[✖]  --name=fp-3e1852b1 and argument fp-dev cannot be used at the same time

$ ./eksctl delete fargateprofile --cluster marc-test-fargate --name ""
[...]
[✖]  invalid Fargate profile: empty name
```

message:
Fargate: more consistently validate input and print help for mandatory input

**Before**:

```console
$ ../eksctl-dist-6d958706/default_darwin_amd64/eksctl create fargateprofile
[✖]  --cluster must be set
```

```console
$ ./eksctl get fargateprofile
[✖]  failed to get Fargate profile(s) for cluster "": InvalidParameter: 1 validation error(s) found.
- minimum field size of 1, ListFargateProfilesInput.ClusterName.
```

```console
$ ./eksctl delete fargateprofile
[✖]  invalid Fargate profile: empty name
```

```console
$ ./eksctl delete fargateprofile --name foo
[ℹ]  deleting Fargate profile "foo"
[✖]  failed to delete Fargate profile "foo": InvalidParameter: 1 validation error(s) found.
- minimum field size of 1, DeleteFargateProfileInput.ClusterName.
```

**After**:

```console
$ ./eksctl create fargateprofile
Create a Fargate profile

Usage: eksctl create fargateprofile [flags]

Fargate flags:
      --name string             Fargate profile's name
      --namespace string        Kubernetes namespace of the workloads to schedule on Fargate
  -l, --labels stringToString   Kubernetes selector labels of the workloads to schedule on Fargate, e.g. k1=v1,k2=v2 (default [])

General flags:
  -c, --cluster string       EKS cluster name
  -r, --region string        AWS region
  -f, --config-file string   load configuration from a file (or stdin if set to '-')
  -w, --wait                 wait for the creation of the Fargate profile before exiting. Profile creation may take a few seconds to a couple of minutes.
      --timeout duration     maximum waiting time for any long-running operation (default 25m0s)

AWS client flags:
  -p, --profile string   AWS credentials profile to use (overrides the AWS_PROFILE environment variable)

Common flags:
  -C, --color string   toggle colorized logs (valid options: true, false, fabulous) (default "true")
  -h, --help           help for this command
  -v, --verbose int    set log level, use 0 to silence, 4 for debugging and 5 for debugging with AWS debug logging (default 3)

Use 'eksctl create fargateprofile [command] --help' for more information about a command.

[✖]  --cluster must be set

dlespiau
message:
build: Change git repository for Apache Thrift

git.apache.org doesn't answer anymore:

```
go: git.apache.org/thrift.git@v0.12.0: unknown revision v0.12.0
go: git.apache.org/thrift.git@v0.0.0-20180902110319-2566ecd5d999: git fetch -f origin refs/heads/*:refs/heads/* refs/tags/*:refs/tags/* in /home/damien/go/pkg/mod/cache/vcs/83dba939f95a790e497d565fc4418400145a1a514f955fa052f662d56e920c3e: exit status 128:
	fatal: unable to access 'https://git.apache.org/thrift.git/': Failed to connect to git.apache.org port 443: Connection timed out
go: error loading module requirements
go: finding git.apache.org/thrift.git v0.0.0-20180902110319-2566ecd5d999
go: finding git.apache.org/thrift.git v0.12.0
go: git.apache.org/thrift.git@v0.12.0: unknown revision v0.12.0
```

The official documentation points at github:

https://thrift.apache.org/lib/go

```
$ go get github.com/apache/thrift/lib/go/thrift/...
```

author: cPu1
message:
Fix upgrading managed nodegroups

Currently, AMIs published for EKS worker nodes are not immediately available for use with managed nodegroups. To work around this, this change uses the AWS EKS Nodegroup API and leaves the ReleaseVersion unset to allow the default behaviour of the API choosing the latest available AMI version.

This change also switches from updating the CloudFormation stack to using the UpdateNodegroupVersion API call, because with the ReleaseVersion no longer being set to the latest AMI release obtained via SSM, some other field must be updated in order to trigger a stack update. Rather than use a hack like updating a label on the nodegroup, we simply use the UpdateNodegroupVersion API call which also gives more control over the update process.

author: mumoshu
message:
feat: CloudFormation Service Role support

In case your role is too restrictive that `eksctl create cluster` fails due to cloudformation reporting insufficient permissions, specify a service role used by CloudFormation to call AWS API while provisioning stacks on your behalf.

```
eksctl create cluster --cfn-role-arn arn:aws:iam:YOUR_AWS_ACCOUNT_ID:role/eksctl
```

Resolves #329

author: benjiro
message:
Improve handling of kube-proxy upgrade (#4021)

Starting from EKS 1.21 AWS has decided it will now include a the commit
sha in the kube version. This causes problems when upgrading kube-proxy
because it sets the image name to include build part of the semver so
image pulls fail.

Starting from 1.18 all kube-proxy images have a postfix of eksbuild.2.
Assume this is true for all release from 1.18 onwards

author: powersj
message:
Add Ubuntu 20.04 Image Support (#2758)

* Added Ubuntu 20.04 Image Support

Starting with EKS 1.18, the official Ubuntu EKS images are based on
Ubuntu 20.04 LTS (Focal). EKS 1.17 is the last release to use
Ubuntu 18.04 LTS (Bionic) as a base.

There are two key changes included:

* Add CLI support for the Ubuntu2004 family
* Create a new bootstrap script specific to Ubuntu2004

Ubuntu 20.04 EKS images, are no longer disabling the
systemd-resolved's DNS stub listener. Without this, the CoreDNS will
assume there is a loop when trying to incorrectly use
/etc/resolv.conf.

* Add automated tests to api for Ubuntu2004 family

* Improve amiFamily JSON schema

* Reduce duplication

* Make sure Ubuntu1804/2004 finds correct images

Co-authored-by: Michael Beaumont <mjboamail@gmail.com>

author: marccarre
message:
Add integration tests for `eksctl install flux` (#1148)

* Add utility to generate random strings (+tests)

* Call git config before committing

... as otherwise, we may commit using the wrong username/email,
and if missing, `git commit` fails with the following:
```
*** Please tell me who you are.

Run

  git config --global user.email "you@example.com"
  git config --global user.name "Your Name"

to set your account's default identity.
Omit --global to set the identity only in this repository.

fatal: unable to auto-detect email address (got '[...]')
```

* Add --git-private-ssh-key-path flag

... to be able to specify SSH private keys for Git to use.
This can be useful for testing & automation.

* Add integration tests for eksctl install flux

* Use Git private SSH key in integration tests (+docs)

* Add openssh to eksctl image

Otherwise, integration tests fail with the following error:

```
(Integration) Create, Get, Scale & Delete when creating a cluster with 1 node and configuring Flux for GitOps
  should not return an error
  /src/integration/creategetdelete_test.go:104
Cloning into '/tmp/eksctl-install-flux-test-clone-814282688'...
ssh -i ~/.ssh/eksctl-bot_id_rsa: line 1: ssh: not found
fatal: Could not read from remote repository.

Please make sure you have the correct access rights
and the repository exists.

• Failure [0.006 seconds]
```

* Add integration tests for Flux Helm operator's installation

* Integration tests: pass --kubeconfig to kubectl in `install flux`

* Integration tests: do NOT override clusterName and region in GitOps profile tests

... as this breaks integration test runs for which `-eksctl.region` and `-ekstl.name` is provided.

* Integration tests: generate kubeconfig when skipping cluster creation

... as when running integration tests like below:
```console
make integration-test-container TEST_V=1 AWS_PROFILE="default-mfa" INTEGRATION_TEST_ARGS="-eksctl.region=ap-northeast-1 -eksctl.cluster=autoscaler -eksctl.create=false -eksctl.delete=false"
```
the creation being skipped, no Kubernetes configuration was previously created, leading to the following test failures:

1)
```
  when creating a cluster with 1 node
  /src/integration/creategetdelete_test.go:47
    should have created a valid kubectl config file [It]
    /src/integration/creategetdelete_test.go:84

    Unexpected error:
        <*os.PathError | 0xc000880c00>: {
            Op: "open",
            Path: "/tmp/kubeconfig",
            Err: 0x2,
        }
        open /tmp/kubeconfig: no such file or directory
    occurred
```

2)
```
  when creating a cluster with 1 node
  /src/integration/creategetdelete_test.go:47
    and configuring Flux for GitOps
    /src/integration/creategetdelete_test.go:103
      should not return an error [It]
      /src/integration/creategetdelete_test.go:104

      Unexpected error:
          <*exec.ExitError | 0xc00042cde0>: {
              ProcessState: {
                  pid: 44,
                  status: 256,
                  rusage: {
                      Utime: {Sec: 0, Usec: 80000},
                      Stime: {Sec: 0, Usec: 10000},
                      Maxrss: 31352,
                      Ixrss: 0,
                      Idrss: 0,
                      Isrss: 0,
                      Minflt: 3621,
                      Majflt: 0,
                      Nswap: 0,
                      Inblock: 0,
                      Oublock: 0,
                      Msgsnd: 0,
                      Msgrcv: 0,
                      Nsignals: 0,
                      Nvcsw: 350,
                      Nivcsw: 97,
                  },
              },
              Stderr: nil,
          }
          exit status 1
      occurred

      /src/integration/flux_utils_test.go:529
```

* Remove utility to generate random strings

... as github.com/kubicorn/kubicorn/pkg/namer is already a dependency and could be used instead for what we need here.

Fix nesting of info text

The text here appears to belong inside the information bubble but due to nesting that is not how it is rendered.

What you see on the page currently is a collapsible info header that does nothing when clicked and this text, which causes confusion because of how it reads when not in the info bubble. author: marccarre
message:
Fargate: pkg/fargate.Client#CreateProfile can now wait for creation (+tests)

Waiting is useful as the Fargate API returns the following error
when trying to create a Fargate profile while another still has its
status set to "CREATING":

```
[✖]  failed to create Fargate profile "dev" on EKS cluster "cluster-16": failed to create Fargate profile "dev" in cluster "cluster-16": ResourceInUseException: Cannot create Fargate Profile dev because cluster cluster-16 currently has Fargate profile default in status CREATING
	status code: 409, request id: 88b6c847-47ac-44eb-ad89-0df199d7e247
```

In particular, if multiple profiles are defined in `ClusterConfig`,
then this error is hit. We therefore need to linearise the creation
of all Fargate profiles by waiting each of them to reach an
appropriate status before moving on to the creation of the next one.

message:
Handle race condition in Fargate profile creation (#3615)

There's a race condition in Fargate that can lead to a Fargate profile not being available in pod scheduler if it's created immediately after cluster becomes Active. To work around this issue, this change adds a delay before creating Fargate profiles.

Co-authored-by: Jake Klein <jake@weave.works>

author: errordeveloper
message:
Add a way for users to provide bootstrap command

This should allow those who _know what their are doing_ to pass
a custom script to run inside of cloud-init. Anyone looking to
use this will need to defined a shell script that would resemble
`bootstrap.{al2,ubuntu}.sh`. This should cater for any of advanced
use-cases, where additional files must be created on EC2 instances
prior to boot or anything of that nature. Alternative approach is
to use a custom AMI, or propose an eksctl feature, but this is
meant as a stop-gap for testing things out.

author: weaveworksbot
message:
Handle aws-node 1.7 initContainer properly (#2734)

Since version 1.7 of AWS VPC CNI plugin for Kubernetes
the DaemonSet consists additionally of one initContainer.

This initContainer needs the same treatment as the main container regarding
usage of the regional image.

Otherwise the consequence would be a failing pod in China regions
or slow image pulls in other regions than us-west-2.

Co-authored-by: Icereed <domi@icereed.net>
Co-authored-by: Mike Beaumont <mjboamail@gmail.com>

author: arnaldo2792
message:
Skip NVIDIA device plugin daemonset in Bottlerocket node groups

The Bottlerocket NVIDIA AMI already provides the NVIDIA device plugin,
so Bottlerocket node groups don't require the NVIDIA device plugin
daemonset.

This change makes sure that clusters with only Bottlerocket nodegroups
don't get the NVIDIA device plugin daemonset. If any of the nodegroups
in the cluster's configuration uses an OS that requires the device
plugin, it will be installed.

Signed-off-by: Arnaldo Garcia Rincon <agarrcia@amazon.com>

author: Callisto13
message:
Undo setting cgroup drivers to systemd

Since we have stopped providing custom bootstrapping scripts and are now
relying on what comes with the AMI, finding the right places to change
the setting for both kubelet and docker is trickier. GPU nodes now fail
to come up. The GPU AMIs are going through some changes, so those
locations will be even harder to pin down for a while.
I am undoing this for now, and plan to look into it later when I have
more time.

author: laghoule
message:
Added a retry loop when PDB isn't respected (or other errors) when running a nodegroup drain (via delete nodegroup)

This changes ensure we don't fail at first try when a drain node receive an error like
"Cannot evict pod as it would violate the pod's disruption budget."

We add a retry count of 60 (5 sec by retry), for a total of 5 min by node.

Tested with an EKS sandbox cluster 1.13.8, and AMI ami-0f2e8e5663e16b436 (amazon-eks-node-1.13-v20190701)

author: marccarre
message:
Fargate: more consistent logging, only log 'creating'/'deleting' at info level for long-running operations

Creating and deleting profiles in an asynchronous operation, but given
that the async. operation itself is quick, in general, we should only
log about the fact it is in progress at debug level.
When the user wants to make this synchronous by passing `--wait`, then
we log about it at info level as it becomes a slower operation.

author: mumoshu
message:
feat: Nodegroup as a resource

`eksctl` now allows you to manage any number of nodegroups other than the initial nodegroup.

Changes:

- `eksctl create nodegroup --cluster CLUSTER_NAME [NODEGROUP_NAME]` is added

  Creates an additional nodegroup.
  The nodegroup name is randomly generated when omitted.

- `eksctl get nodegroup --cluster CLUSTER_NAME` is added

  Lists all the nodegroups including the initial one and the additional ones.

- `eksctl delete nodegroup --cluster CLUSTER_NAME NODEGROUP_NAME` is added

  Deletes a nodegroup by name.

- `eksctl create cluster` has been changed to accept an optional `--nodegroup NODEGROUP_NAME` that specifies the nodegroup name.

- `eksctl delete cluster CLUSTER_NAME` has been changed to recursively delete all the nodegroups including additional ones.

- `eksctl scale nodegroup --cluster CLUSTER_NAME NODEGROUP_NAME` has been changed to accept the target nodegroup name as the second argument

Checklist:

- [x] Code compiles correctly (i.e `make build`)
- [x] Added tests that cover your change (if possible)
- [x] All tests passing (i.e. `make test`)
- Added/modified documentation as required (such as the README)
- Added yourself to the `humans.txt` file

Acknowledgements:

This is a successor of #281 and #332.

All the original credits goes to Richard Case <richard.case@outlook.com> who has started #281. Thanks a lot, Richard!

author: toricls
message:
Added CloudWatch Support

This change enables nodegroups to put metrics and logs into CloudWatch via monitoring, log-forwarding agents including the CloudWatch agent.

Users can enable this by adding “cloudWatch: true” under “nodeGroups.[x].iam.withAddonPolicies” as other addon policies.

At this time, the “CloudWatchAgentServerPolicy” managed policy has the following actions for any resources:
```
cloudwatch:PutMetricData
ec2:DescribeTags
logs:PutLogEvents
logs:DescribeLogStreams
logs:DescribeLogGroups
logs:CreateLogStream
logs:CreateLogGroup
```
and also has the following action for “arn:aws:ssm:*:*:parameter/AmazonCloudWatch-*”
```
ssm:GetParameter
```

author: cPu1
message:
Remove support for --wait flag in `create fargateprofile`

When multiple profiles are present in a config file, the second profile fails to create because, by default, we don't wait for the previous profile to become ACTIVE before initiating creation of the second profile. The fact that the AWS Fargate API disallows creation of a profile if another profile is still being created, is an implementation detail of eksctl which users shouldn't be exposed to, or have control over. The `--wait` flag allows a user to break profile creation and hence should not be supported.

author: rndstr
message:
Fix (plan) output when updating k8s addons

For the commands `utils update-aws-node` and `utils update-coredns` when
used in dry-run mode, it now returns `already up-to-date` if the image
tag of the deployment/daemonset matches what is in the built-in assets.

While this does _not_ confirm a run with `--approve` is a no-op (since the
current image might not be region-aware or other parts in the manifest
differ), it will tell you whether the version is up-to-date.

When running the commands with `--approve`, the built-in manifests will be
applied idempotently in any case no matter whether the image tags match
or not.

author: 2opremio
message:
Pin base dependencies image

This is needed to achieve reproducible builds and avoid unexpected build cache misses.

Unfortunately the `golang` dockerhub image doesn't tag minor versions of Alpine
(e.g. it provides golang:1.12.6-alpine3.9 but not golang:1.12.6-alpine3.9.4
making all the images mutable when patches are released).

Thus, we ping the image digest instead of a tag.

As a side note: there is no need to bump the version of the dependencies image
(`EKSCTL_DEPENDENCIES_IMAGE` in the Makefile) since the change doesn't affect
layering.

author: treacher
message:
No longer default SSH allow to true when SSH Public Keys are defined
and SSH allow is set to false.

This change was made to allow people to be able to define a KeyName
without an ingress rule of port 22 open to the VPC being set as a side
effect. This feature is useful in the case where you want to manage
SSH access with your own seperate security group but you still want to
explicitly set the SSH key.

Changed the logic for defaults so that when you define an SSH key and
set SSH to disabled it will no longer set SSH to enabled.

Removed the requirement of having SSH.Allow set to true when defining the
PublicKeyName in the template.

Provided an example where `allow: false` is set with a comment about what the
new behavior is in the ssh-keys example.

author: cPu1
message:
Fix upgrading nodegroups with old template format (#2572)

* Fix upgrading nodegroups with old template format

goformation unmarshals an attribute reference as an array. For old templates, this was causing the reference to `"Fn::GetAtt": "NodeInstanceRole.Arn"` to be unmarshalled as `"Fn::GetAtt": ["NodeInstanceRole", "Arn"]`, which, in turn, was triggering an update on this resource. However, when upgrading a nodegroup, CloudFormation does not permit combining release version updates with other updates, and this resulted in an error.

* Use LT instead of Compare

author: richardcase
message:
Changed region handling

The region handling for the commands has changed. Previously, if
you didn't specify the region flag (-r/--region) then we would
default to us-west-2 even if you had a different region specified
in the AWS environment variables or shared config. With this change
we only default to us-west-2 if there is no region specified using the
flay AND there is no region coming from the AWS shared config /
environment variables.

Issue #235

author: marccarre
message:
Fargate: create fargateprofile: improve usage's clarity and consistency

- clarified --namespace and --labels' usage
- lowercased --timeout's description

**Before**:
```console
Fargate flags:
      --name string             Fargate profile's name
      --namespace string        Kubernetes namespace from which workloads should be selected to be scheduled on Fargate.
  -l, --labels stringToString   Kubernetes selector labels to match in order to select workloads to schedule on Fargate (default [])

General flags:
  -c, --cluster string       EKS cluster name
  -r, --region string        AWS region
  -f, --config-file string   load configuration from a file (or stdin if set to '-')
  -w, --wait                 wait for wait for the creation of the Fargate profile, which may take from a couple seconds to a couple minutes. before exiting
      --timeout duration     Maximum waiting time for any long-running operation (default 25m0s)
```

**After**:
```console
Fargate flags:
      --name string             Fargate profile's name
      --namespace string        Kubernetes namespace of the workloads to schedule on Fargate
  -l, --labels stringToString   Kubernetes selector labels of the workloads to schedule on Fargate, e.g. k1=v1,k2=v2 (default [])

General flags:
  -c, --cluster string       EKS cluster name
  -r, --region string        AWS region
  -f, --config-file string   load configuration from a file (or stdin if set to '-')
  -w, --wait                 wait for the creation of the Fargate profile before exiting. Profile creation may take a few seconds to a couple of minutes.
      --timeout duration     maximum waiting time for any long-running operation (default 25m0s)
```

author: errordeveloper
message:
Delete nodegroups when there are dangling resources

This is an initial change towards avoiding deletion issues whenever
we end-up with dangling resources that got created while cluster was
in use, and didn't go away cleanly.

Here we introduce two things:
- `DeleteStack` checks if stack that is about to be deleted already
  has `DELETE_FAILED` status, and bails out if that's the case;
  this behaviour can be controller with `force` argument
- during cluster deletion, if we cannot delete a nodegroup right away,
  we go and try to cleanup danlging ENIs (which somehow didn't used
  to be an issue, but recently this started to cause failures in
  integration tests)
- at the moment, we only try to delete these interfaces during cluster
  deletion, and nodegroup deletion may still fail and we don't have
  cleanup/retry mode there yet

author: PaulMaddox
message:
Added AWS X-Ray Support

This change adds an `--xray-access` CLI flag, that when specified will
add an IAM policy to the node group IAM role. The IAM policy allows
outbound write access to AWS X-Ray.

The specific policy allows access to:
```
xray:PutTraceSegments
xray:PutTelemetryRecords
xray:GetSamplingRules
xray:GetSamplingTargets
xray:GetSamplingStatisticSummaries
```

This is useful, as AWS App Mesh (supported with `--appmesh-access` flag)
can optionally push metrics into AWS X-Ray. For an example of this see
the screenshots [here](https://github.com/PaulMaddox/aws-appmesh-helm).

Also see https://github.com/PaulMaddox/aws-appmesh-helm/issues/1

author: cPu1
message:
Allow new resources to be created during cluster stack update

ClusterResourceSet builds a CloudFormation template using the ClusterConfig as input and skips creation of certain resources if the user has supplied their own resource (e.g., ClusterConfig.VPC.SecurityGroup) This works fine during cluster creation.

During an update, the VPC fields in ClusterConfig supplied by the user are ignored because user-supplied updates to VPC are not (yet) supported. However, before building a new template, the code loads the VPC config from the existing cluster's stack output, which results in ClusterResourceSet skipping execution of code that'd otherwise be executed when these fields aren't supplied by the user. As a consequence, any update logic that adds code that's conditionally executed, depending on whether a field was user-supplied or not, will be skipped and the updated stack will not have the new resources.

This change fixes creating resources that are created when VPC.SecurityGroup and VPC.SharedNodeSecurityGroup are not user-supplied.

message:
Set the version of an addon with an (alpha)numeric version that has no prefix or suffix (#3646) 

Set the version of an addon with a (alpha)numeric version that has no prefix or suffix.

* the addon version can be empty, set to latest, set to the full form of the version such as `v1.7.5-eksbuild-1`, or a short form such as `1.7.5` or even `1.7.5-eksbuild`.

* eksctl finds and matches the given version value with the latest version available, if one exists

author: archis-polyverse
message:
Add Timeouts

This commit fixes issue: https://github.com/weaveworks/eksctl/issues/23

By accepting a timeout parameter, in number of seconds, it allows
the polling operations to exit after a default of five minutes (300 seconds),
but one that is modifiable.

This is immensely useful in automation and scripted scenarios.

Also ran 'go fmt' which may have caused some whitespace changes in
other files. Will undo them if they are undesired.

author: marccarre
message:
Remove timeout on Git commands (#1247)

Prior to this commit, if an user was required to enter their SSH key's
credentials (e.g. if identities got removed from the SSH agent), but
wouldn't enter these within 20 seconds, then eksctl would fail and
the command would have to be re-run from scratch, which can be rather
frustrating, especially as credentials would have to be entered several
times during a gitops apply command, for example.

After this change, we no longer enforce a timeout on Git commands, so
eksctl will wait indefinitely for the end-user to enter their
credentials, and will then resume work from there once entered.

author: errordeveloper
message:
Ensure defaulting and validation works correctly in all commands

Some commands that don't have `--config-file` have custom defaulting
and validation logic. This brings the time that logic is called
before general validation and defaulting is called (i.e. `cmd.NewCtl`).
Namely, it ensures that `eksctl get ng`, `eksctl scale ng` and
`eksctl utils write-kubeconfig` work correctly.

author: overdrive3000
message:
Changes EFS IAM Policy Resource

When IAM AddOn Policy for EFS is set to true the policy is generated
specifying a wrong (fake) resource ARN
`arn:aws:elasticfilesystem:us-west-2:123456789012:file-system/*`.

The resource ARN in the policy statement should be in the format of
`arn:aws:elasticfilesystem:<REGION>:<AWS_ACCOUNT>:file-system/*` or simply
allow all resources `*` as is being done in the other addons like the EBS
one.

More information about EFS API Permissions can be found at:
https://docs.aws.amazon.com/efs/latest/ug/efs-api-permissions-ref.html

Issue #828

author: 2opremio
message:
Add `eksctl install flux` command (#1064)

* Add `eksctl install flux` command

* Bump github/2opremio/flux

* Fix typo

* Refine missing pod error detection

* Avoid commit error when manifests already exist

* Fix missing parameter

* Address code review: flux -> Flux in CLI args' help

* Address code review: clearer call to action w.r.t. Flux SSH key

* Use upstream Flux version

Now that https://github.com/fluxcd/flux/pull/2287 is merged we can use
upstream Flux

* gofmt -s -w pkg/ctl/install/install.go

* Address code review: use CreateOrUpdate instead of kubectl

* Address code review: improve use of RawExtensions and CreateOrUpdate

* Address code review: improved output of eksctl help install flux

* Address code review: rename import: k8serrors -> apierrors

... in order to follow the same conventions as elsewhere in the codebase.

* Address code review: add more context to comments?

* Address code review: clearer command description?

* Address code review: explain why we return Flux's SSH key

* Rename kubernetes.JoinManifest* to ConcatManifest*

... and also change ConcatManifests to become a variadic function, since more flexible to use.

* Add utilities to generate Kubernetes Namespace objects (+tests)

* Use kubernetes.Manifest{,YAML} utilities to install Flux

* Address code review: extract check of existence of namespace

+ update comments

* Address code review: re-read manifests once amended

* Create the Flux namespace in the same way as all other resources

* Fix rebase: GetCredentials -> RefreshClusterConfig

* Add pkg/kubernetes/client.go#RawClient#ClientOrUpdate higher-level method

This should hopefully make it easier to leverage RawClient for simpler cases.

author: rndstr
message:
Remove outdated and generated version/release.go

The file `pkg/version/release.go` is generated when doing a release
through `tag-release.sh` and also committed into its release branch but
never merged back to master.

The one in master is from before we changed this process and can be
confusing for third parties vendoring and seeing the code with an
outdated tag.

author: hintofbasil
message:
Parallel drain all nodegroups (#5146)

Currently all nodegroups are drained in serial but the nodes in each node group
are drained in parallel.  This change updates this logic to drain all nodes
across all node groups in parallel - up a maximum defined by the --parallel
flag.

This significantly speeds up draining for clusters with a large number of small
node groups.  Especially if some of the nodes in these node groups take longer
to drain than others.

This has the side affect of cordoning all nodes in all node groups before
beginning the actual draining process.  This should be the preferred behaviour
but may come as a surprise to some users - especially those that assume the
cordoning is actually the node being drained.

Co-authored-by: Gergely Brautigam <182850+Skarlso@users.noreply.github.com>

author: marccarre
message:
No longer print usage/help on errors

This is to avoid printing usage/help on genuine runtime errors.
However, a side effect of this is that we now also no longer print
usage/help on input validation errors either.

That being said, given:

- we're trying to sanitise/simplify `eksctl`'s code at the moment,
- other CLI also do NOT print any usage/help on input validation errors
  e.g. `kubectl`,

it was decided between Martina, Chetan and I that it didn't matter too
much for now.

author: mumoshu
message:
feat: kube2iam/kiam/kube-aws-iam-controller support

This adds two flags and one nodegroup config key to `eksctl`:

- `--node-role-policies` for replacing the whole set of IAM policies associated to the eksctl-managed node role.
  This just exposes the existing configuration key `attachPolicyARNs` for a little ease-of-use, like other advanced flags.
- `--node-role-name` for specifying the exact name of the IAM role for nodes, as well as the corresponding nodegroup config key `instanceRoleName`. This implicitly enable the `NamedIAM` cfn capability.

The flags are marked hidden show that they are not shown in the command help. This is done to make it easier to be removed in near future.

Resolves #398

author: marccarre
message:
gitops apply: use temp dir instead of --output-path (#1337)

Given end-users provide their configuration Git repository as an input,
it makes little sense to return it, cloned locally, as an output.
Instead, `eksctl gitops apply` now:

- no longer expose `--output-path`,
- uses a temporary directory instead, for cloning and file operations,
- expects that the end-user already has, or soon will clone this
  repository, and will "pull" the latest changes themselves, once
  they have run `eksctl gitops apply`.

author: rndstr
message:
Add `eksctl util aws-auth` command for manipulation

The command `eksctl util -aws-auth` allows to manipulate the `aws-auth`
configmap in `kube-system`.

It supports the following actions
- `--add-admin-role=<arn>`
- `--remove-role=<arn>`
- `--add-account=<number>`
- `--remove-account=<number>`

author: brianpursley
message:
The reserved memory calculation was changed in amazon-eks-ami to be based on pod density (#2443)

(11*maxPodsPerNode+255) instead of total memory.
See https://github.com/awslabs/amazon-eks-ami/blob/21426e27e3845319dbca92e7df32e5c4b984a1d1/files/bootstrap.sh#L163

This commit introduces a new MaxPodsPerNode property on InstanceTypeInfo and populates it
using the data from maxpods.go so that it will be available for calculating the default memory
to reserve. It removes the Memory property from InstanceTypeInfo because it is no longer needed.

This commit also updates related unit tests. It fixes some unit tests which reference instance types which no
longer exist and adds a check to make sure instance types which are expected to exist actually exist, and those
which are not expected to exist do not exist.

Co-authored-by: Mike Beaumont <mjboamail@gmail.com>

author: marccarre
message:
Enforce SSH Git URLs in install flux & gitops apply commands (#1232)

* Add pkg/git/Options#ValidateURL (+tests)

To have all the validation logic on the `Options` `struct` itself,
instead of being scattered across commands' `main`s.
This should also help enforcing consistency across commands.

* install flux no longer duplicates pkg/git/Options

Before this commit, `eksctl install flux` was using a configuration
`struct` which had the same fields as `pkg/git/Options`, but
flattened. There is no good reason for such duplication, especially
as business logic is being added to `pkg/git/Options` to validates
its fields: let's keep things DRY!

* install flux & apply gitops now validate with git.Options.ValidateURL

... instead of each having their own currently weak, and duplicated
input validation logic.
This helps enforce consistency across commands, hence improving the
UX, while also reducing the chances of having invalid input making it
through.

* More consistent flag description for Git SSH URL

... `install flux` & `apply gitops`.
This should help clarify to the end user that `eksctl` currently only
supports SSH Git URLs, and provides an example of the accepted format.

* No colon after e.g.

* Use errors.Wrap instead of Wrapf where possible

* Use giturls.Parse to check the scheme is SSH/Git
